Objectives & goals for CA1¶

  1. Perform image classification on the CIFAR-100 dataset and obtain a good competitive accuracy score (low avoidable bias), simultaneously searching for a model that does not overfit.

  2. Try out different training methodology and experiment with SOTA model architectures, training procedures and data augmentation without hurting the performance of model

Prediction task and background research¶

  • Can we develop a deep learning model to classify images in the CIFAR-100 dataset, particularly using a CNN architecture

  • This is a multi-class classification task

Reading dataset¶

  1. We load the data using load_data and it returns 2 tuples for us
  2. For the purpose of training and evaluating the model, we need to have our data in the form of 3 sets: train, validation and test. Ideally, the training data is used to train the model, validation data is used to perform tuning of models, and the test data will act as a final independant evaluation of the performance of the final model and its ability to generalize well.(low variance)
  3. Furthermore, the model's performance can also be evaluated on the validation data on each epoch of training.
  4. Hence, we will perform a 20% split on the train set (.8) to allocate 10000 images for the validation set (.2).
  5. Since CIFAR100 dataset is not extremely large (not millions of records), i felt that a 20% split would be relevant. furthermore, we are also making decisions based on validation set. Hence, we must try to avoid overfitting the validation set.
  • X_train: 40000
  • X_val: 10000
  • X_test: 10000

Preprocessing¶

  • Before we feed data into models, we need to perform preprocessing.

Pixel rescaling

  • Initially, the pixel values for each image in dataset are between 0 and 255.
  • We need to rescale the pixel values to the range of 0 and 1. This is to handle the strong influence very large or small pixel values may pose. For example, if we do not scale, the network learns weights from features that are from different scales, and the large feature may 'drown' out the small features. Not rescaling the pixels can introduce the problem of exploding gradients, due to the high range of pixels.
  • We will divide the pixel values by the maximum value of 255.
  • This was a crucial step as it would improve optimization (faster) and especially critical for optimizers such as SGD, where it converges better and faster when pixel scales are similar. One hot encoding for target labels
  • We will also one hot encode the target variable y from the label encoded format

Modelling¶

Evaluation metrics & optimization techniques¶

  • We need to select our metrics/loss (to be optimized) along with our optimization techniques to sepcify under the .compile() method later.
  • Optimization algorithms aims to minimize cost function, which is difference between the predicted data and the actual values

Metrics: Categorical accuracy

  1. Since this is a multi-class classification task, and given the fact we have one-hot encoded our y labels, categorical_accuracy will be used to evaluate the model's performance. However, if we choose to specify accuracy, it will not matter as Keras uses categorical_accuracy internally for multi-class classification. Src.

Loss function: Categorical cross entropy

  1. As our prediction task is multi-class classification, we need to use categorical cross entropy as our loss function. We will not use sparse_categorical_crossentropy as we have one hot encoded the y labels. This loss can be used to measure the difference between two probability distributions. $$Loss = -\frac{1}{N} \sum^N_{i=1}{[y_{i}log(\hat{y}_i) + (1 - y_i) ⋅ log(1 - \hat{y}_i)]}$$ $$\text{where $y_{i}$ is i'th true label, while $\hat{y}_i$ is i'th predicted label }$$

Optimizer: SGD with Nesterov Momentum vs Adaptive methods (like adam)

  • Prior to modelling, we have to carefully select the optimization algorithm, particularly we want a optimizer that can enable the model to generalize well, with low variance, while simultaneously having low avoidable bias. I have shortlisted 2 optimization methods particular SGD or Adam (adaptive method)
  • After research, it was found that adaptive optimization methods such as Adam have been proven to discover solutions that generalize poorly compared to Stochastic gradient descent [4], these methods tend to perform well on early stages but SGD then outperforms further into training. It was also shown that the lack of generalization in performance of adaptive methods come from the non-uniform scaling of the gradient [5]. From another study of gradient noise, it was discovered that SGD is more locally unstable than Adam at sharp minimas, and can better escape from them and converge to minima at the flat or asymmetric basins/valleys, which often have better generalization performance over sharp minimas. Hence, this highlights how SGD is able to generalize better as compared to adam [7]. It was further noted that although adaptive methods yielded better training performance, it was not able to generalize as well as SGD, as shown in poor performance in benchmark dev and test set. [5]
  • Despite attempts to improve the generalization performance of Adam, such as introducing ND ADAM [6], which preserves gradient direction. However this improvement sacrifises the rapid initial speed of adam. Hence, there is still a gap between SGD and adaptive methods when it comes of generalization ability when it comes to image classification, with SGD being more reliable. However, one thing to note is that Adam has faster convergeance over SGD over lesser epochs. However, since we want our model to be robust, I choose to go with SGD with nesterov momentum first, and decide if we need to change it. We will proceed with SGD first

Activation Functions:

  • Most of the time, we will be using a rectified linear unit activation function, so as to capture non linearities in the feature map.
  • I did not want to have many sigmoid activation function, as extreme values snap to 1 or -1, this would be challenging for the learning algorithm to continue and update the weights to improve the model.
  • RELU on the other hand, is more robust and is able to handle the problem of vanishing gradients, where the gradient diminishes as it is propagated through the network
  • Softmax: We will use softmax function usually for the last layer for the model to indicate to us the probability of the output class of being true. Softmax will also be used since this is a multi class classification problem

Optimization Hyperparameters

Initial Learning rate

  • The initial learning rate will be set to 0.5, this is consistent with the implementation details of Deep Pyramidal networks paper for this task (The initial learning rate is set to 0.5 for CIFAR-100). [9] I chose to follow their implementation as it was found to be compatible with pyramid nets, together with my fears that a very small learning rate however may lead to slow convergence. However, I may change the learning rate later for certain CNN architectures.

Momentum

  • Momentum helps to speed up gradient descent and minimize oscillations, reducing fluctuations while approaching the optimal solution, which improves efficiency and speed of convergence. More specifically, momentum helps parameter vector to build up velocity in any direction with gradient descent.
  • We will be using a series of models such as pyramid net later on, and it was found that momentum of 0.9 worked well in the Deep pyramidal networks implementation [9]. Furthermore, this value is quite popular among State of the art CNN architectures such as Densely connected CNN [10] and WideResNets [8] and even Residual networks [13]. I decided to follow this value.

Source: https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1742-6596/1229/1/012046/pdf

Reduce Learning rate on plateau¶

  • I decided to follow the pyramidal residual networks paper authors' implementation to decay learning rate after some time. However, the main difference between my implementation and theirs is i reduce my learning rate when a particular metric has stopped improving. On the other hand, their implementation reduces the learning rate after a certain epoch.
  • The reason why I made this choice is becuase of the following:
    • If i were to keep to a specific learning rate until a certain epoch, I have fears that the model will reach a plateau and metrics does not improve before arriving at that certain epoch. Hence, I wanted a dynamic learning rate that changes based on the performance of the metric of my choice.
    • Therefore, I used ReduceLROnPlateau, to counter the problem of plateaus which slows down the neural network training. The idea behind implementing this is as follows: we want to select an initial learning rate to quickly approach minima, and we want to reduce the learning rate when the validation accuracy stumbles upon plateaus. Hence, to further update the parameters, we need to reduce the learning rate. The purpose of this callback is to decrease the learning rate to allow us to descend into the minimum/ optimal solution, instead of jumping back and fourth far above the optimal solution.
    • I decided to set the factor of which the learning rate will be reduced to be 0.35, while keeping a lower patience. Personally, I wanted the model to have a taste of a variety of learning rates (reduce LR many times, but reduction is less each time), so to thoroughly explore the loss function space. Lowering the factor of learning rate would mean that we would reduce the learning rate by a larger multiplier, which means that the learning rate will shrink much faster, and we may face the problem of stagnant weight updates much earlier

Starting Model Hyperparameters¶

Batch size

  • For batch sizes, there was sufficient evidence provided by Nitish, et al. [11], that indicated that a larger batch would result in degradation in the quality of the model, affecting the ability to generalize. This is due to the fact that large batch methods tend to converge to sharp minimizers, leading to high variance issues. [11] To play my cards safe, i pick a batch size of 128, this also requires less memory. Furthermore, noise gradient updates as a result of lower batch size can help model reach lower error, resulting in a regularizing effect, increasing the robustness of the model.

Epochs

  • I decided to set my epochs to 100, i felt this was an optimal number, we can compensate the training epochs with data augmentation to prevent overfitting.

L2 Regularization parameter

  1. I decided to set weight decay to 0.0005 (l2 reg param).

def plot_loss_acc_graph(result):
    epochs = list(range(1, len(result['loss']) + 1))
    sns.set()
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20, 9))
    ax1.plot(epochs,result['loss'], label='Training Loss', marker='o',)
    ax1.plot(epochs,result['val_loss'], label='Validation Loss', marker='o',)
    ax1.set_title('Training and Validation Loss')
    ax1.set_xlabel('Epochs')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Loss')
    ax1.locator_params(integer=True)

    ax1.legend()

    ax2.plot(epochs,result['categorical_accuracy'], label='Training Accuracy', marker='o',)
    ax2.plot(epochs, result['val_categorical_accuracy'], label='Validation Accuracy', marker='o',)
    ax2.set_title('Training and Validation Accuracy')
    ax2.set_xlabel('Epochs')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Accuracy')
    ax2.locator_params(integer=True)

    ax2.legend()
    return fig

class EvaluatorHistory:
    def __init__(self) -> None:
        self.history = []
    def evaluate_model(self,model:Model,train_ds,batch_size, val_ds,compile_config,wandb_run, epochs=EPOCHS, monitor = 'val_categorical_accuracy', plot=True, additional_cb = None, augmentation = False):
        """
        Takes in uncompiled model and compile and train it
        """
        K.clear_session()
        model = self.compile_model(model, **compile_config)
        d= dict()        
        self.model_name = '{}'.format(model.name)
        self.model_path = 'models/{}/'.format(self.model_name)
        if not os.path.exists(self.model_path):
          os.makedirs(self.model_path)
        self.model_logs = os.path.join(self.model_path, 'training.csv')
        # Check if we have trained the model before, if yes print out the logs (to save time)
        try:
            self.get_logs(self.model_name)
            # print(self.model_logs)
            history = pd.read_csv('{}'.format(self.model_logs))
            fig = plot_loss_acc_graph(history)
            fig.show()
            return
        except Exception as e:
            pass
        
        self.model_weights = os.path.join(wandb_run.dir,'model-best.h5' )
        
        self.training_log = os.path.join(wandb_run.dir, 'output.log')
        cb = [CSVLogger(self.model_logs,append=False),
                    TerminateOnNaN(), reduce_lr ]

            
        # ==================================================================================================
        
        if additional_cb is not None:
            cb+=additional_cb
        try:
            if augmentation:
                results = model.fit(train_ds,validation_data=val_ds, epochs=epochs, callbacks=cb,batch_size=batch_size)
            else:
                X_train, y_train = train_ds
                results = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=epochs, validation_data=val_ds, batch_size=batch_size, callbacks=cb)
            history = results.history
        except KeyboardInterrupt:
            history = pd.read_csv('{}'.format(self.model_logs))
        wandb_run.finish()
        if plot:
            fig = plot_loss_acc_graph(history)
            fig.show()
        d['Model Name'] = self.model_name
        d['Model Logs'] = self.model_logs
        d['Epoch'] = len(history["loss"])
        d['Model Weights/Model'] = self.model_weights
        best_idx = np.argmax(history['val_categorical_accuracy'])
        d["Train Loss"] = history["loss"][best_idx]
        d["Val Loss"] = history["val_loss"][best_idx]
        d["Train Accuracy"] = history["categorical_accuracy"][best_idx]
        d["Val Accuracy"] = history['val_categorical_accuracy'][best_idx]
        d['Training Log Info'] = self.training_log
        K.clear_session()
        self.history.append(pd.Series(d))
        self.save_history()
        return pd.Series(d).to_frame().T.set_index('Model Name')

    def compile_model(self,model:Model, optimizer, loss, metrics):
        # Compiles a model
        model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss=loss, metrics = metrics)
        return model
    def get_model(self, model_name:str, model):
        models_df = self.get_history()
        compiled_model = self.compile_model(model, **COMPILE_CONFIG)
        try:
            compiled_model.load_weights(models_df.loc[models_df['Model Name'] == model_name, 'Model Weights/Model'].item())
        except:
            compiled_model.load_weights(r''.format(models_df.loc[models_df['Model Name'] == model_name, 'Model Weights/Model'].item()))
        return compiled_model
    def get_logs(self, model_name:str):
        """
        Get model logs if it has been recorded before in self.history
        """
        models_df = self.get_history()
        try:
            file_loc = str(models_df.loc[models_df['Model Name'] == model_name, 'Training Log Info'].item())
            # print(file_loc)
            with open(file_loc, 'r') as f:
                print("".join(line for line in f if not line.isspace()))
            # return
        except:
            file_loc = str(models_df.loc[models_df['Model Name'] == model_name, 'Training Log Info'].item())
            # print(file_loc)
            with open(r''.format(file_loc), 'r') as f:
                print("".join(line for line in f if not line.isspace()))
        return 

    def save_history(self):
        if not os.path.exists('archive'):
          os.makedirs('archive')
        pd.DataFrame(self.history).to_csv(f'archive/{self.model_name}.csv', index=False, mode= 'w+')
    def get_history(self, strc='BottleNeck'):
        try:
            df = pd.concat([pd.read_csv(f) for f in glob.glob('archive/'+'*{}*.csv'.format(strc))])
            # self.history.append(df)
            return df.drop(columns='Model Logs')
        except:
            pass

PyramidNet¶

  • Pyramid nets act as an improvement based on residual networks and the pre-activation res nets. It is found that by gradually increasing the feature map dimensions, instead of doubling the filters every set number of residual blocks which is often done. This results in the improvement of classification accuracy, and greater generalization ability [14].
  • In CNN architectures, feature map dimensions are not increased unless downsampling occurs. Hence, pyramid net seeks to address this by increasing the feature map dimensions gradually. In this implementation, we will be using the additive pyramid net, which is tested to be better than the multiplicative counterpart

Specific network configurations

  • Furthermore, we will be using the pyramid bottleneck architecture, which gradually increases feature map dimensions. However, to match the increasing feature map dimensions of input and output, we perform zero pad identity mapping short cut connection, which was found to be generally better than other shortcut connections. This can be seen from Deep Pyramidal Residual Networks [14], where they compared zero padded short cut connections with project connections. It was discovered that project shortcut connections yielded poor performance for deep neural networks with many residual units as compared to zero padded shortcut during their testings. [14]
  • Next, I also decided to follow the original authors recommendation to remove the first RELU, and placing a batch norm layer after the final convolution layer for the pyramidNet bottleneck architecture. Both of these changes were found to enhance performance.

L2 Regularization

  • Next, I also added l2 regularization to prevent overfitting, l2 reg penalises the model as it gets more complex. It updates the loss function to penalize the model in proportion to the size of weights. This has a regularizing effect, as larger weights result in a more complex and less stable model, whereas smaller weights would reduce the power of hidden neurons, where it would result in a less complex model, therefore the model is less likely to overfit as a result of noise in data. This l2 regularization implementation is consistent with what is done in the pyramidNet paper.

Motivation

  • I decided to go with PyramidNet due to its lower parameter count despite of its depth due to the fact that the feature map gradually increases.

class BottleNeckBlock(Model):
    def __init__(self, no_filters  ,stride, pool = False):
        super(BottleNeckBlock, self).__init__()
        self.downsample = pool
        # self.maxpooling = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(stride, stride), strides=(stride, stride), padding='valid')

        self.bn0 = BatchNormalization()

        self.conv1 = get_conv(filters = no_filters, kernel_size=1, strides=1, padding='valid' , use_bias = False, kernel_regularizer = L2(WEIGHT_DECAY))
        self.bn1 = BatchNormalization()
        self.act1 = Activation('relu')

        self.conv2 = get_conv(filters = no_filters, kernel_size=3, strides=stride, padding='same' , use_bias = False, kernel_regularizer = L2(WEIGHT_DECAY))
        self.bn2 = BatchNormalization()
        self.act2 = Activation('relu')


        self.conv3 = get_conv(filters = no_filters*4, kernel_size=1, strides=1, padding='valid', use_bias = False, kernel_regularizer = L2(WEIGHT_DECAY))
        self.bn3 = BatchNormalization()
        # self.shake = shakedrop
        self.add = Add()
    def call(self, x):
        out = self.bn0(x)
        
        out = self.conv1(out)
        out = self.bn1(out)
        out = self.act1(out)

        out = self.conv2(out)
        out = self.bn2(out)
        out = self.act2(out)

        out = self.conv3(out)
        out = self.bn3(out)
        # Found to improve performance with bn after last conv

        shortcut = MaxPooling2D((2,2) , strides = (2,2))(x) if self.downsample else x   

        if K.int_shape(shortcut)[3] != K.int_shape(out)[3]:
            shortcut = tf.pad(shortcut, tf.constant( [[0,0] , [0,0] , [0,0] , [0 ,    K.int_shape(out)[3] -  K.int_shape(shortcut)[3] ]] ))
        

        return self.add([out + shortcut])

class PyramidNet(Model):
    def __init__(self  , alpha , N , block = BottleNeckBlock):
        super().__init__()
        n = (N-2)//9
        self.increment = alpha / (n*3.0)
        self.totallayer = n*3.0
        self.block = block 
        self.n_layers = 1

        self.conv1 = Conv2D(16 ,3,1,'same'  , use_bias = False )
        self.batchnorm1 = BatchNormalization()
        self.no_filters = 16


        self.group1 = self.group_init(n  , 1  ) 
        self.group2 = self.group_init(n, 2  ) 
        self.group3 = self.group_init(n  , 2 )  


        self.batchnorm2 = BatchNormalization()
        self.activation = Activation('relu')
        

        self.avgpool = GlobalAveragePooling2D()


        self.out = Dense(100 , activation = 'softmax' , dtype = 'float32')
    def group_init(self, no_layers,stride  ):
        tempmodel = []
        self.no_filters += self.increment

        tempmodel.append(self.block(int(round(self.no_filters) ), stride , pool = (stride != 1) ) )
        self.n_layers +=1
        for _ in range(no_layers -1 ):
            self.no_filters += self.increment
            tempmodel.append(self.block(int(round(self.no_filters)), stride = 1 , pool = False ,  )  )
            self.n_layers +=1
        return tempmodel

    def call(self , x):
        x = self.conv1(x)
        x = self.batchnorm1(x)
        for layer in self.group1:
            x = layer(x)
        for i,layer in enumerate(self.group2):
            x = layer(x)
        for layer in self.group3:
            x = layer(x)
 
 
        x = self.batchnorm2(x)
        x = self.activation(x)
        x = self.avgpool(x)       
        x = self.out(x)
        return x

Bottleneck pyramidal networks insights

  1. We can see that our bottleneck pyramidnet without any augmentation completely outperforms the baseline models in terms of validation and train accuracy. It has achieved near perfect train accuracy, however the validation accuracy is very poor with only 65%, with an enormous gap of 35% from train set.
  2. We can deduce that our model is overfitting severely as seen from learning curves, hence we need to apply regularization techniques to reduce overfitting, and improve the generalization performance of the model.
  3. I also noticed that the early stopping stopped the model too early, which did not give the model enough time to train, hence for the next model we will increase early stopping to 20, effectively allowing the model to run for more epochs.
  4. Next, we also can see the loss is steadily decreasing, but it is still a noisy decrease.

Model Improvement (Regularization techniques)¶

  1. Next, we will apply a series of techniques to reduce overfitting.
  2. We will apply shake drop regularization.

Shakedrop regularization

  1. Shakedrop regularization is inspired from shake shake regularization. It is an effective regularization method, that can be applied to model families such as pyramid nets, residual nets, etc.
  2. Shakedrop is derived from mixing shakeshake and random drop, and its main idea is to disturb and add noise to the training process. This disturbance prevents the network parameters from being captured in local minima.

Cutmix augmentation

  • To improve the performance of the model, we will employ a strong augmentation technique called cutmix to further reduce overfitting, introduced in Regularization Strategy to Train Strong Classifiers with Localizable Features. (Yun et al., 2019)
  • Cutmix replaces a patch of an image with a patch of another image from training set. The labels are also mixed proportionally to the number of pixels of combined images.
  • In a way, cutmix minimizes information loss & increases localization ability by making the model to focus on less discriminative parts of the object being classified.

import functools
def tf_custom_gradient_method(f):
    @functools.wraps(f)
    def wrapped(self, *args, **kwargs):
        if not hasattr(self, '_tf_custom_gradient_wrappers'):
            self._tf_custom_gradient_wrappers = {}
        if f not in self._tf_custom_gradient_wrappers:
            self._tf_custom_gradient_wrappers[f] = tf.custom_gradient(lambda *a, **kw: f(self, *a, **kw))
        return self._tf_custom_gradient_wrappers[f](*args, **kwargs)
    return wrapped

class ShakeDrop(Layer):
    def __init__(self, p, alphas, betas, **kwargs):
        self.p = p
        self.alphas = alphas
        self.betas = betas
        super().__init__(**kwargs)

    def call(self, x, training):
        p = tf.cast(self.p, x.dtype)
        if training:
            return self._shake(x, p, self.alphas[0], self.alphas[1], self.betas[0], self.betas[1])
        else:
            return x * ( p)

    def get_config(self):
        base_config = super().get_config()
        base_config['p'] = self.p
        base_config['alphas'] = self.alphas
        base_config['betas'] = self.betas
        return base_config

    @tf.custom_gradient
    @staticmethod
    def _shake( x, p, alpha_min, alpha_max, beta_min, beta_max):
        basegate= tf.random.uniform((), dtype=p.dtype) > (p)
        alpha_min = tf.cast(alpha_min, x.dtype)
        alpha_max = tf.cast(alpha_max, x.dtype)
        shape = [tf.shape(x)[0], 1, 1, 1]
        beta_min = tf.cast(beta_min, x.dtype)
        beta_max = tf.cast(beta_max, x.dtype)
        return tf.cond(basegate,lambda : (x * tf.random.uniform(shape, alpha_min, alpha_max, dtype=x.dtype))  , lambda :  x ) , lambda dy : (tf.cond(basegate , lambda : ( dy* tf.random.uniform(shape, beta_min, beta_max, dtype=dy.dtype) ), lambda : (dy) ) ,None, None, None, None, None )

class BottleNeckBlock(Model):
    def __init__(self, no_filters  ,stride, pool = False , shakedrop = 0):
        super(BottleNeckBlock, self).__init__()
        self.downsample = pool
        self.maxpooling = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(stride, stride), strides=(stride, stride), padding='valid')

        self.bn0 = BatchNormalization()

        self.conv1 = get_conv(filters = no_filters, kernel_size=1, strides=1, padding='valid' , use_bias = False, kernel_regularizer = L2(WEIGHT_DECAY))
        self.bn1 = BatchNormalization()
        self.act1 = Activation('relu')

        self.conv2 = get_conv(filters = no_filters, kernel_size=3, strides=stride, padding='same' , use_bias = False, kernel_regularizer = L2(WEIGHT_DECAY))
        self.bn2 = BatchNormalization()
        self.act2 = Activation('relu')


        self.conv3 = get_conv(filters = no_filters*4, kernel_size=1, strides=1, padding='valid', use_bias = False, kernel_regularizer = L2(WEIGHT_DECAY))
        self.bn3 = BatchNormalization()
        self.shake = shakedrop
        self.shakedrop =  ShakeDrop(alphas = (-1,1) , betas = (0,1)  ,p = self.shake )
        self.add = Add()
    def call(self, x):
        out = self.bn0(x)
        
        out = self.conv1(out)
        out = self.bn1(out)
        out = self.act1(out)

        out = self.conv2(out)
        out = self.bn2(out)
        out = self.act2(out)

        out = self.conv3(out)
        out = self.bn3(out)
        # Found to improve performance with bn after last conv
        
        out =self.shakedrop(out)

        shortcut = MaxPooling2D((2,2) , strides = (2,2))(x) if self.downsample else x   

        if K.int_shape(shortcut)[3] != K.int_shape(out)[3]:
            shortcut = tf.pad(shortcut, tf.constant( [[0,0] , [0,0] , [0,0] , [0 ,    K.int_shape(out)[3] -  K.int_shape(shortcut)[3] ]] ))
        

        return self.add([out + shortcut])

class PyramidNet(Model):
    def __init__(self  , alpha , N , block = BottleNeckBlock):
        super().__init__()
        n = (N-2)//9
    
        self.increment = alpha / (n*3.0)
        self.totallayer = n*3.0
        self.block = block 
        self.n_layers = 1

        self.conv1 = Conv2D(16 ,3,1,'same'  , use_bias = False )
        self.batchnorm1 = BatchNormalization()
        self.no_filters = 16


        self.group1 = self.group_init(n  , 1  ) 
        self.group2 = self.group_init(n, 2  ) 
        self.group3 = self.group_init(n  , 2 )  


        self.batchnorm2 = BatchNormalization()
        self.activation = Activation('relu')
        

        self.avgpool = GlobalAveragePooling2D()


        self.out = Dense(100 , activation = 'softmax' , dtype = 'float32')
    def group_init(self, no_layers,stride  ):
        tempmodel = []
        self.no_filters += self.increment

        tempmodel.append(self.block(int(round(self.no_filters) ), stride , pool = (stride != 1)  , shakedrop = 1- ((self.n_layers / self.totallayer )*0.5 ) ))
        self.n_layers +=1
        for _ in range(no_layers -1 ):
            self.no_filters += self.increment
            tempmodel.append(self.block(int(round(self.no_filters)), stride = 1 , pool = False , shakedrop =  1- ((self.n_layers / self.totallayer )*0.5 ) )  )
            self.n_layers +=1
        return tempmodel

    def call(self , x):
        x = self.conv1(x)
        x = self.batchnorm1(x)
        for layer in self.group1:
            x = layer(x)
        for i,layer in enumerate(self.group2):
            x = layer(x)
        for layer in self.group3:
            x = layer(x)
 
 
        x = self.batchnorm2(x)
        x = self.activation(x)
        x = self.avgpool(x)       
        x = self.out(x)
        return x

def sample_beta_distribution(size, concentration_0=0.2, concentration_1=0.2):
  gamma_1_sample = tf.random.gamma(shape=[size], alpha=concentration_1)
  gamma_2_sample = tf.random.gamma(shape=[size], alpha=concentration_0)
  return gamma_1_sample / (gamma_1_sample + gamma_2_sample)


@tf.function
def get_box(lambda_value):
  cut_rat = tf.math.sqrt(1.0 - lambda_value)
  image_wh = IMG_SIZE[0]
  cut_wh = image_wh * cut_rat  # rw
  cut_wh = tf.cast(cut_wh, tf.int32)

  cut_x = tf.random.uniform((1,), minval=0, maxval=image_wh, dtype=tf.int32)  # rx
  cut_y = tf.random.uniform((1,), minval=0, maxval=image_wh, dtype=tf.int32)  # ry

  boundaryx1 = tf.clip_by_value(cut_x[0] - cut_wh // 2, 0, image_wh)
  boundaryy1 = tf.clip_by_value(cut_y[0] - cut_wh // 2, 0, image_wh)
  bbx2 = tf.clip_by_value(cut_x[0] + cut_wh // 2, 0, image_wh)
  bby2 = tf.clip_by_value(cut_y[0] + cut_wh // 2, 0, image_wh)

  target_h = bby2 - boundaryy1
  if target_h == 0:
      target_h += 1

  target_w = bbx2 - boundaryx1
  if target_w == 0:
      target_w += 1

  return boundaryx1, boundaryy1, target_h, target_w


@tf.function
def cutmix(train_ds_one, train_ds_two):
  (image1, label1), (image2, label2) = train_ds_one, train_ds_two
  image_size = IMG_SIZE[0]
  alpha = [1]
  beta = [1]

  # Get a sample from the Beta distribution
  lambda_value = sample_beta_distribution(1, alpha, beta)

  # Define Lambda
  lambda_value = lambda_value[0][0]

  # Get the bounding box offsets, heights and widths
  boundaryx1, boundaryy1, target_h, target_w = get_box(lambda_value)

  # Get a patch from the second image (`image2`)
  crop2 = tf.image.crop_to_bounding_box(
      image2, boundaryy1, boundaryx1, target_h, target_w
  )
  # Pad the `image2` patch (`crop2`) with the same offset
  image2 = tf.image.pad_to_bounding_box(
      crop2, boundaryy1, boundaryx1, image_size, image_size
  )
  # Get a patch from the first image (`image1`)
  crop1 = tf.image.crop_to_bounding_box(
      image1, boundaryy1, boundaryx1, target_h, target_w
  )
  # Pad the `image1` patch (`crop1`) with the same offset
  img1 = tf.image.pad_to_bounding_box(
      crop1, boundaryy1, boundaryx1, image_size, image_size
  )

  # Modify the first image by subtracting the patch from `image1`
  # (before applying the `image2` patch)
  image1 = image1 - img1
  # Add the modified `image1` and `image2`  together to get the CutMix image
  image = image1 + image2

  # Adjust Lambda in accordance to the pixel ration
  lambda_value = 1 - (target_w * target_h) / (image_size * image_size)
  lambda_value = tf.cast(lambda_value, tf.float32)

  # Combine the labels of both images
  label = lambda_value * label1 + (1 - lambda_value) * label2
  return image, label

def set_up_cut_mix(X_train, y_train):
    AUTO = tf.data.AUTOTUNE
    train_ds_one = (
        tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_train, y_train))
        .shuffle(2048)
    )
    train_ds_two = (
        tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_train, y_train))
        .shuffle(2048)  
    )
    train_ds = tf.data.Dataset.zip((train_ds_one, train_ds_two))
    
    train_ds = (train_ds.shuffle(1024).map(cutmix, num_parallel_calls=AUTO)
    .batch(BATCHSIZE)
    .prefetch(AUTO)
    )

    val_ds = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_val, y_val)).shuffle(2048).batch(BATCHSIZE).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
    return train_ds,val_ds
